## Supabase Tables

- waitlist — id, email, created_at
- profiles — id, username, display_name, email, created_at
- ideas — id, user_id, title, description, status (build/refine/revisit), confidence_score, created_at
- quiz_answers — id, idea_id, question_number, question, answer, created_at
- decisions — id, idea_id, market_score, founder_score, decision, decision_headline, decision_summary, market_analysis, founder_analysis, next_step, full_plan, created_at
- launch_packs — id, idea_id, one_pager, mvp_scope, prd, created_at

## The Three Decisions (never call them verdicts)

- Build it — strong signals, high founder fit, high Q7 enthusiasm
- Needs refinement — addressable gaps, fixable in 2-4 weeks, Q7 must be high
- Revisit later — structural issues or low Q7. You cannot refine your way to passion.

## Security Rules

- Always use RLS on every Supabase table
- Never expose service role key — anon key only in frontend
- All keys in .env.local — never commit to GitHub
- Auth protect all pages except /, /waitlist, /auth

## The Product Philosophy

Compete on confidence not features.
Every screen should ask: does this make the user feel more confident about their idea?